      "writtenOn": "2020-07-17T16:32:12Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Suggestion:\n\n  sort(key: keyof T, dir: SortDirection) {\n    this._data.sort((a, b) \u003d\u003e {\n      let left \u003d a[key] as unknown;\n      let right \u003d b[key] as unknown;\n\n      if (dir \u003d\u003d\u003d \"down\") {\n        [right, left] \u003d [left, right];\n      }\n\n      if (typeof left \u003d\u003d\u003d \"number\" \u0026\u0026 typeof right \u003d\u003d\u003d \"number\") {\n        return left - right;\n      }\n\n      if (typeof left \u003d\u003d\u003d \"string\" \u0026\u0026 typeof right \u003d\u003d\u003d \"string\") {\n        return left.localeCompare(right);\n      }\n\n      throw new Error(\n        `Trying to sort by key \"${key}\", which is neither a number nor a string.`);\n    });\n    this.dispatchEvent(new CustomEvent(\u0027sort-changed\u0027, {bubbles: true}));\n  }\n\nRationale:\n- The compiler will complain when client code tries to sort by a key that does not exist on type T.\n- No need for @ts-ignore; we can preserve type safety by casting to unknown and then narrowing down with typeof.\n- No need to provide the alpha argument.\n- Less code repetition, less surface area for bugs.",
